= Research Statement

My research investigates the significant role of entertainment media as both a reflector and catalyst of societal values and economic behavior, focusing on how narratives in television, film, literature, and music influence real-world outcomes. At the heart of my work lies a novel methodological contribution: leveraging generative artificial intelligence to transform rich, unstructured narrative content into structured data amenable to rigorous econometric analysis. This approach enables high-frequency, scalable examination of culture’s impact on human behavior, aligning closely with Carnegie Mellon University’s dedication to pioneering innovation across disciplines and addressing complex societal challenges through technology.

In my job market paper, I focus on Latin American telenovelas, developing the Female Empowerment Index (FEI) by applying generative AI to analyze nearly 2,000 synopses. This index, grounded in an enhanced Bechdel-Wallace framework, enables me to causally identify how media exposure contributes to narrowing gender gaps in labor participation. Employing a credible instrumental variable strategy that exploits quasi-random variation in television signal reception due to geographic topology in Mexico, I demonstrate that increased exposure to portrayals of women in non-traditional careers leads to meaningful labor market gains. Importantly, this research highlights the power of nuanced cultural narratives to shape economic outcomes, an intersection at the core of the Economics of Information Systems and Digitization themes emphasized by the Heinz College.

Complementing this, my work on preferences for redistribution examines how telenovelas depicting inequality influence public support for redistributive policies. By comparing various natural language processing techniques and applying state-of-the-art generative AI classification, I reveal counterintuitive shifts in political preferences driven by misrepresented narratives of marginalized groups. This work speaks directly to the societal and managerial implications of technology and information, critical areas identified in the job advertisement.

Looking forward, my research agenda aims to expand this pipeline to incorporate multimodal generative AI models capable of analyzing visual and auditory media content, thus capturing the full spectrum of cultural influence beyond text. This effort promises to enhance interdisciplinary collaboration at the intersection of data science, social science, and decision science, leveraging cutting-edge AI tools such as GPT-4o and Gemini as platforms for innovation.

I also intend to explore the media supply side, investigating how political environments shape narrative content production and dissemination. This line of inquiry resonates with Heinz College’s commitment to tackling conventional and unconventional challenges and aligns with potential collaborative opportunities with experts in policy, information systems, and technology and society.

Further, my approach fosters opportunities for undergraduate engagement and mentorship, reflecting Carnegie Mellon’s emphasis on educational excellence and broad participation. Through managing research assistants for data collection and AI benchmarking, I aim to cultivate a collaborative and intellectually curious research environment.

Overall, my research agenda integrates rigorous empirical methods, cutting-edge technological innovation, and a deep commitment to societal impact—core values shared by Carnegie Mellon University and its Economics Department at the Heinz College. I am enthusiastic about contributing to and benefiting from this vibrant interdisciplinary ecosystem that champions high-quality education, diversity, and transformative scholarship at the nexus of economics, information systems, and policy.
